            "content_en": "\u003cb\u003eEmphatic structures\u003c/b\u003e are used to highlight or emphasize specific information in a sentence. They help us draw attention to what we consider most important.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eThe main emphatic structures include:\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e1. \u003cb\u003eCleft sentences with 'It is/was':\u003c/b\u003e Used to emphasize any part of the sentence\u003cbr\u003e• It + be + emphasized element + that/who/which + rest of sentence\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e2. \u003cb\u003eWhat-clefts (Pseudo-cleft sentences):\u003c/b\u003e Used to emphasize actions or objects\u003cbr\u003e• What + subject + verb + be + emphasized element\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e3. \u003cb\u003eInversion for emphasis:\u003c/b\u003e Used with negative adverbials\u003cbr\u003e• Negative adverbial + auxiliary verb + subject + main verb\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e4. \u003cb\u003eDo/Does/Did for emphasis:\u003c/b\u003e Used to emphasize the action itself\u003cbr\u003e• Subject + do/does/did + base verb",
